# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ahimsa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:ahimsa/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The **2014 anti-war protests in Russia** refers to a series of anti-war demonstrations opposing the Russian military intervention in Ukraine that took place in Russia in 2014.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protesters held two anti-war protest rallies on 2 and 15 March 2014.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The latter, known as the **March of Peace** (Russian: Марш Мира, *Marsh Mira*), took place in Moscow a day before the Crimean referendum.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The protests have been the largest in Russia since the 2011–2013 Russian protests by the Russian opposition against the alleged electoral fraud committed by United Russia during the 2011 Russian legislative election.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Reuters reported that around 20,000 people participated in the 15 March demonstrations.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 1 March, five people who were picketing next to the Federation Council building against the invasion of Ukraine were arrested.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The next day about 200 people protested at the building of the Russian Ministry of Defense in Moscow against Russian military involvement.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] About 500 people also gathered to protest on the Manezhnaya Square in Moscow and the same number of people on the Saint Isaac's Square in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 2 March, about eleven protesters demonstrated in Yekaterinburg against Russian involvement, with some wrapped in the Ukrainian flag.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 15 March, for a rally in support of Ukraine in Yekaterinburg, according to various sources, between 400 and 600 people left, including the Mayor of the city Yevgeny Roizman.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests were also held in Chelyabinsk on the same day.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The opposition to the military intervention was also expressed by rock musician Andrey Makarevich, who wrote in particular: "You want war with Ukraine?
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] It will not be the way it was with Abkhazia: the folks on the Maidan have been hardened and know what they are fighting for – for their country, their independence. [...] We have to live with them.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] But it's up to them how they want to live".
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The Professor of the Department of Philosophy at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations Andrey Zubov was fired for his article in *Vedomosti*, criticizing Russian military intervention.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Andrei Zubov, a professor at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations, who compared Russian actions in Crimea to the Anschluss of Austria, was threatened.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Alexandr Chuyev, the leader of the pro-Kremlin Spravedlivaya Rossiya party, also objected to Russian intervention in Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Boris Akunin, popular Russian writer, predicted that Russia's moves would lead to political and economic isolation.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests against the Russian intervention also occurred outside Russian embassies in London, Berlin, Vilnius and Ankara on 2 March.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Protests against the Russian intervention in Crimea also took place in Cologne and outside the Russian Consulate in Bonn, Germany, on 15 March.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] In August, about a dozen activists were arrested outside the Ukrainian Embassy in Moscow for protesting against Russian president Vladimir Putin.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Another anti-war rally with about 5,000 to 20,000 demonstrators took place on Pushkinskaya Square in Moscow on 21 September 2014.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] *The Washington Post* reported that "tens of thousands" protested the war in Ukraine with a peace march in downtown Moscow "under heavy police supervision".
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] There were minor scuffles with pro-Russian supporters, but no serious violence or arrests were reported.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] About a thousand people also gathered outside the Kazan Cathedral in Saint Petersburg to protest against Russia's involvement in Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] Thousands of people around the world supported this event by holding anti-war demonstrations on the same day.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] In the US, San Francisco, New York, Washington, DC, Los Angeles, Seattle, Houston and Boston took part in the protest activities.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 19 March 2014, the anti-war congress of Russian intelligentsia took place in Moscow.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] On 19 March 2014, a group of Russian scientists published an open letter to the Russian Ministry of Communications.
[src:ahimsa/2014-anti-war-protests-in-russia] The letter demanded the Ministry to check the television programs of Dmitry Kiselev for signs of extremism and incitement of ethnic hatred.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Following the Russo-Ukrainian war on 24 February 2022, anti-war demonstrations and protests broke out across Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As well as the demonstrations, a number of petitions and open letters have been penned in opposition to the war, and a number of public figures, both cultural and political, have released statements against the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The protests have been met with widespread repression by the Russian authorities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, at least 14,906 people were detained from 24 February to 13 March 2022.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Human rights organisations and reporters have raised concerns of police brutality during arrests and OVD-Info reported several cases of protesters being tortured under detention.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The government has also moved to crackdown on other forms of opposition to the war, including introducing widespread censorship measures.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Other individuals who signed anti-war petitions have faced reprisals.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After Russian president Vladimir Putin announced a partial mobilization of Russia's military reserves on 21 September, over 2,000 people were detained in mass street protests in the following days.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the afternoon of the invasion, the Investigative Committee of Russia issued a warning to Russians that they would face legal repercussions for joining unsanctioned protests related to "the tense foreign political situation".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The opposition activist Marina Litvinovich called on Instagram for street protests on the evening of 24 February but was detained by police as she left her house.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] That evening, thousands took to the streets in cities across Russia to protest the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The largest demonstrations were in Moscow, where 2,000 protesters gathered near Pushkinskaya Square, and Saint Petersburg, where up to 1,000 protesters gathered.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Hundreds demonstrated in Yekaterinburg, and there were also demonstrations in Chelyabinsk, Nizhny Novgorod, Novosibirsk and Perm, including other cities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the evening of the day of the invasion, according to the OVD-Info monitor, there had been 1,820 arrests in 58 cities, of which 1,002 were carried out in Moscow.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Russia's interior ministry justified these arrests with "coronavirus restrictions, including on public events".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the following day, 25 February, further protests had continued in Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Saint Petersburg several hundred people gathered in the city center, chanting "No to war!" OVD-Info reported 437 detentions in 26 Russian cities on that day, including 226 in Moscow and 130 in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, some Russian protesters chose to reduce the chances of arrest by staging single-person protests in Moscow and other city squares.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Others gathered in small groups to move more nimbly around the streets.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Yekaterinburg, hundreds gathered, shouting "No to war!".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Throughout the day at least 469 people were arrested in 34 cities, of which around half in Moscow, bringing the total number of arrests to over 3,000.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The protests coincided with the seventh anniversary of the murder of the opposition politician Boris Nemtsov, and arrests took place at an improvised memorial outside the Kremlin where Nemtsov was shot.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Around 1,000 people gathered for a spontaneous anti-war rally near Great Gostiny Dvor in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, by early Sunday evening, police had detained at least 900 Russians in 44 cities, bringing the total number of arrests to over 4,000 since the war had begun.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the day, that number had grown to around 2,710 arrests (at least 5,844 in total since the beginning of the war), including at least 1,269 arrests in Moscow and 1,034 in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Members of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, the People's Freedom Party, and Yabloko, spoke out against the invasion.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the same day, a van with markings that read "People, wake up!", "This is war", "Putin is scum!" in Russian crashed and caught fire in Pushkinskaya Square.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 1 March, reports and photographs appeared in social media, also republished and confirmed by *Novaya Gazeta*, showing primary school children behind bars, arrested by police in Moscow for laying flowers at the Ukrainian embassy and holding signs saying the repeated "No to war".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A special detention center set up in Yekaterinburg ran out of room for prisoners arrested from protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 2 March, the artist Yelena Osipova, aged 77 and born to survivors of the Siege of Leningrad, was among those arrested at an anti-war protest in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Videos of her arrest were widely shared on social media platforms Twitter and Reddit.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Police action against the protesters continued on the following day.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 4 March, the activist Yulia Galyamina was detained and held in custody pending trial, charged with violating the law on public events by trying to organise an anti-war protest.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 5 March, ahead of protests planned for 6 March, police raided, searched and detained hundreds of Russian journalists, politicians and activists.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 6 March, there were protests in at least 60 cities, including Vladivostok, Irkutsk and Khabarovsk.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] OVD-Info reported over 5,000 arrests throughout the day.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Russian interior ministry reported over 3,500 detentions.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A video showing Kemerovo Oblast governor Sergey Tsivilyov attempting to justify the invasion to protesters that day went viral.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The total number of arrests reached 13,000 overall on 6 March.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Police ordered the women laying flowers at the Gostiny Dvor in Saint Petersburg to disperse, and made over five arrests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Moscow the Alexander Garden was closed to block access to the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, so flowers were left nearby.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] 11 girls were detained in Moscow's Manezhnaya Square.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At least 93 people, at least 60 of them in Moscow, were detained.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 15 March, Anastasia Parshkova was arrested for standing alone before the Cathedral of Christ the Saviour in Moscow with a placard bearing the words "6th Commandment.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She was taken to the police station, according to the Avtozak Live telegram channel.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The art historian Maria Silina has characterized Parshkova's action – redeploying symbols of the Russian Orthodox Church to critique the alliance between Orthodox religion and military ideology – as an example of détournement typical of contemporary feminist art activism in Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the week following International Women's Day, several videos went viral on social media showing Russian police arresting protesters for simply holding up a blank sign.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Another arrest which went viral was that of a woman arrested for holding up a small sign that simply read "два слова" ("two words" in Russian).
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of March, mass protests were reported to have largely subsided due to repression from the authorities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some smaller individual acts of opposition against the war continued.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Sochi, Diana Isakova and other activists prepared flyers with QR codes that led to an online text "Time to change!" written by Isakova, criticising Putin as a dictator and calling for citizens to organise and carry out nonviolent resistance against the Putin government.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 17 April, Isakova and her colleagues distributed the flyers.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Isakova was later arrested but was not prosecuted.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The audience staged an anti-war protest at the concert of the Russian group Kis-Kis in Saint Petersburg in May.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Unconfirmed reports circulated about a protest planned for 12 June, Russia Day, which eventually did not take place.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Instead, authorities in Moscow detained 50 people, using facial recognition software.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 21 September, the Vesna movement called for country-wide demonstrations in response to Putin's announcement of partial mobilization of Russia's military reserves, following setbacks for the Russian military during the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kharkiv Oblast.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Multiple small-scale protests followed in several cities, including Moscow, Saint Petersburg, Yekaterinburg, Novosibirsk and Tomsk.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] More than 1,311 protesters in 38 cities had been detained by the end of the day, according to OVD-Info.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 September, anti-mobilization rallies organized by Vesna took place in many cities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The rallies were marked by mass detentions not only of protesters, but also of ordinary passers-by.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to OVD-Info, more than 750 people were detained by 22:30 Moscow time.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 25 September, the women of Yakutsk went to a rally under the slogans "We will not give up our husbands", "No to genocide", "No to war".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] People gathered in Uosohhai, a traditional round dance symbolising the blessing of mothers for the safe return of their husbands and sons.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The women were soon dispersed by the security forces.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the same day, residents of Endirey, Khasavyurtovsky District of Dagestan, took part in a rally against mobilization.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The police fired live rounds into the air in an attempt to disperse the rally.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the evening of 25 September, a rally was held in Makhachkala, the capital of Dagestan.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At the rally, protesters clashed with the police, who in turn opened fire into the air.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By the end of the day, the protest was dispersed by Rosgvardia troops.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As well as protests, activists have also posted anti-war stickers around neighbourhoods, have written anti-war messages on banknotes, and have hung posters that mimic official missing person posters, but that instead contain information about Russian soldiers that have been killed in the invasion.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The artist Alexandra Skochilenko was arrested for allegedly replacing supermarket labels with messages protesting the Mariupol theatre airstrike, and jailed for eight weeks pending trial under the Russian fake news laws.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In Voronezh and Lukhovitsy, cases of arson of military enlistment offices and police departments in Krasnoyarsk and Smolensk were recorded.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Molotov cocktails were used in all of them.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As of beginning-June, at least 15 cases of arson directed at military recruitment centres had been recorded.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 March, a video was released on TikTok showing a protester throwing Molotov cocktails at the Moscow Kremlin walls.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 28 March, Moscow student Anastasia Levashova was sentenced to two years in prison for having thrown a Molotov cocktail at police during an anti-war rally.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At least four teachers have been arrested after criticising the invasion in their classrooms.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 14 March, Marina Ovsyannikova, an editor at Channel One Russia, disrupted the set of the channel's main news program *Vremya* during prime time by holding up a sign with an anti-war message.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Do not believe the propaganda, here you are being lied to.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ovsyannikova, the daughter of a Ukrainian father and a Russian mother, also released a pre-recorded video at OVD-Info in which she expressed shame for her part in spreading "Kremlin propaganda" at Channel One.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She was detained by police later that evening and was released, according to TASS.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ovsyannikova was detained and later released again on 17 July after staging a lone protest at the Sophia Embankment, in front of the Kremlin, two days prior.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Others have taken to attempt to remove symbols of pro-Russian actions, such as the letter Z.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A man, who later fled to Armenia, reportedly stopped a car with the letter Z on its windscreen with a shovel and ordered the car's inhabitants to rip it off.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 September, a gunman opened fire at a draft office in Irkutsk Oblast, injuring one senior official.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 8 May 2023, the Yav Art Group presented an installation titled "Russian Cyberpunk", where prostheses painted with Gzhel patterns were attached to human silhouettes.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The project was swiftly dismantled by authorities after its installation.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some Russian soldiers have been reported to have disobeyed orders to join the invasion.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 12 March, it was reported that around 80 marines had refused to fight after being deployed to Kherson and were returned to Crimea.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 7 April, Pskov newspaper Pskovskaya Gubernia reported that around 60 Russian paratroopers in Belarus had refused such orders, further reporting that Russian commanders were blocking attempts by soldiers to resign from the Russian Armed Forces and referring those soldiers to prosecutors instead.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In the weeks preceding the invasion, there were signs that anti-war sentiment was growing in Saint Petersburg.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] At the beginning of February, over 150 prominent Russian activists, authors, and academics signed an open letter, 'If Only There Is No War!', protesting the "party of war in the Russian leadership" and state media.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the invasion, Russian Nobel Peace Prize winner Dmitry Muratov announced that the *Novaya Gazeta* newspaper would publish its next edition in both Ukrainian and Russian.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Another letter condemning the war was signed by over 250 scientists, and a third open letter was signed by almost 200 municipal council members in Moscow and other cities.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 24 February, human rights activist Lev Ponomaryov started an online petition to protest against the invasion, garnering 289,000 signatures by the end of the day.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 1 March, the petition had gathered more than a million votes.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, a petition for the impeachment of Putin was published by a Russian citizen on the Change.org website, gathering more than 200,000 signatures by the end of 27 February.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some of the petition signers lost their jobs.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] More than 30,000 technology workers, 6,000 medical workers, 3,400 architects, more than 4,300 teachers, more than 17,000 artists, 5,000 scientists, and 2,000 actors, directors, and other creative figures signed open letters calling for Putin's government to stop the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some Russians who signed petitions against Russia's war in Ukraine lost their jobs.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] They are dying through the fault of those who preferred weapons instead of peaceful diplomacy. ....
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Igor Kochetkov, the head of the Russian LGBT Network, launched an open letter against the war and stating that "There are a lot of problems in our country, including the spread of anti-human ideas, which often come from high-ranking officials.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Let's start 'denazification' with them." The open letter received signatures from 150 Russian LGBT+ rights activists.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Representatives of Russian arts and culture workers initiated an open letter expressing solidarity with the Ukrainian people and protesting against the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] As of 23:00 Moscow time on 27 February 2022, the letter was signed by 17,000 people.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Lev Ponomaryov initiated a petition titled "Остановить войну с Украиной! – Нет войне" ("Stop the war with Ukraine! – No to war").
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 4 March, the petition had been signed by more than 1.18 million Russians.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In April 2023, anti-Kremlin activists gathered at a Paris rally organised by Navalny's team and urged the European Union (EU) to ban Svetlana Maniovich, ex-wife of Timur Ivanov, from living in Europe and freeze her assets.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ivanov had already been sanctioned by the EU in October 2022, and was considered by the EU to be responsible for the Russian war effort at large.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Relatives of some Russian officials who justify Russia's war against Ukraine have also expressed their disagreement with the Kremlin's decision through the hashtag "No to war!".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Among them was Liza Peskova, the daughter of the official representative of the Kremlin Dmitry Peskov.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The white-blue-white flag is an anti-war symbol created by removing the red from the Russian flag.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to anti-war protesters, the red represented blood and violence, and the flag attempts to evoke the legacy of the historic Novgorod Republic as an example of democracy.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] However, not all protesters appreciated the flag.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Maria Motuznaya (an opposition activist) had criticised the justification for the removal red stripe of the flag.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] A version of the Russian national anthem proposed in early 1917 after the February Revolution that overthrew the monarchy and turned Russia into a republic that lasted until October 1917.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the Civil War, it was used by Russian emigration, including on radio broadcasting to dissidents in the Soviet Union.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In 2022, the song again became popular among supporters of the anti-war movement.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The slogan "Russia will be free", already popular among the Russian opposition has been adopted by the anti-war protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Some protesters have used green ribbons as a symbol of opposition to the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Both the Russian United Democratic "Yabloko" Party and the Party of People's Freedom condemned the impending invasion of Ukraine several days before 24 February 2022.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Both of these parties opposed the illegal annexation of Crimea and hold moderately pro-Ukrainian positions.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Yabloko party published a petition demanding the withdrawal of troops from the Ukrainian-Russian border on 13 February 2022.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Although the party continues to legally exist, dozens of Yabloko members, politicians, and activists have been arrested or detained since 24 February.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The Communist Party of the Russian Federation (KPRF) officially supports the invasion and is often characterized as a controlled opposition to Putin's government, however, some youth and left-wing factions within the party have opposed the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Two KPRF deputies have spoken up against the war: Mikhail Matveyev and Oleg Smolin.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] KPRF senator Vyacheslav Markhayev has also spoken against the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 27 May 2022, two KPRF lawmakers from the Legislative Assembly of Primorsky Krai were kicked out of the oblast's KPRF group and two others were reprimanded by the party after presenting a statement in opposition to the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 15 February, the website of Russian political party New People, which is also known as a controlled opposition and a spoiler party, released a statement by Sardana Avksentyeva, condemning the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the start of the invasion, leader of the party, Alexey Nechayev, made statements in support of military action.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Avksentyeva's anti-war statement was deleted, and she herself later supported the invasion: "And I feel that today we must give our military an opportunity to complete their work...
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] However, one of the New People deputies of the State Duma, Sangadji Tarbaev, has publicly condemned the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Valery Gartung, also a State Duma deputy and a member of A Just Russia — For Truth party (which supports the invasion), also denounced it in Facebook, and later commented his post to Republic.ru.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Mikhail Gorbachev, the last CPSU General Secretary and the head of state of the Soviet Union, stated that "everything possible must be done to stop the threat of a nuclear war".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, the Gorbachev Foundation stated: "In connection with Russia's military operation in Ukraine, begun on February 24, we affirm the need for an early cessation of hostilities and immediate start of peace negotiations.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 27 February, Russian politician Lyudmila Narusova, a member of the Federation Council, stated in a television interview: "I do not identify myself with those representatives of the state that speak out in favor of the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] I think they themselves do not know what they are doing.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] They are following orders without thinking." Arkady Dvorkovich, who served as a Deputy Prime Minister from 2012 to 2018, condemned Russia's invasion of Ukraine and said that "Wars are the worst things one might face in life...including this war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] My thoughts are with Ukrainian civilians." On 23 March, Putin's longtime advisor and Russian climate envoy Anatoly Chubais resigned from his position and left Russia due to his opposition to the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Alexei Navalny, the opposition leader who was imprisoned in January 2021, called Putin an "obviously insane tsar" and urged Russians to continue daily street protests: "Go out onto the main square of your city every weekday at 19.00 and at 14.00 at weekends and on holidays".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Other groups which have expressed their opposition to the war include the Revolutionary Workers Party, the Libertarian Party of Russia, Socialist Alternative, the Pirate Party of Russia, the United Communist Party, the Left Bloc and Autonomous Action.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ukrainian-born Russian politician and diplomat Natalia Poklonskaya, who rose to prominence during Russia's annexation of Crimea, called the invasion a catastrophe, also adding "People are dying, houses and entire cities are destroyed [leaving] millions of refugees.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] My two native countries are killing each other, that's not what I wanted and it's not what I want".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She also said that Ukraine's society has "changed" in the eight years since the war in Donbas with pro-Russian separatists was ongoing and that Ukrainians "would not greet Russia with flowers".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] She also criticized the Z military symbol.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] According to *The Moscow Times*, Poklonskaya's break with Russia's official line that the Russian invasion of Ukraine is a "special military operation" to "de-Nazify and demilitarize" Ukraine was practically unheard of for a sitting official.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 9 September, seven council members from Smolninsky District Council in St.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Petersburg passed a resolution which called on the State Duma to impeach president Putin for "high treason" due to his handling of the war in Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] After the invasion began on 24 February, several Russian celebrities, including pop star Valery Meladze, television host Ivan Urgant and television presenter Ksenia Sobchak, unambiguously criticized it on social media.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The comedian and television presenter Maxim Galkin and television comedian Alexander Gudkov also condemned the war, as did actress Chulpan Khamatova and actor Konstantin Khabensky.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Ukrainian-born pop star Svetlana Loboda asked "How is this possible?
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Lord, stop all this!" Figure skater Evgenia Medvedeva called for "this all [to end] as soon as possible, like a bad dream".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Chess player Yan Nepomniachtchi tweeted in protest: "History has seen many Black Thursdays.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] But today is blacker than the others. #saynotowar".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Tennis world number one Daniil Medvedev and world number seven Andrey Rublev both spoke out in favour of peace on the day of the invasion.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On the following day Rublev wrote "No war please" on the camera after winning his match.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The hip-hop artist Oxxxymiron cancelled upcoming shows and called for mass protest, calling the invasion "a crime and a catastrophe".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Yelena Kovalskaya resigned as director of the state-owned Meyerhold Theater Center, writing that it was "impossible to work for a murderer and receive salary from him".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Pianist and composer Evgeny Kissin described Russia's invasion as a crime that cannot be justified.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The pianist Alexander Melnikov said "I'm furious with [Putin's government] for making me feel guilty about being Russian." Pop singer Sergey Lazarev called for the war to stop.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 25 February, the ice hockey star Alex Ovechkin, an ardent Putin supporter, made an ambiguous statement against the war without mentioning Ukraine or Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 26 February, Georgian basketball player Tornike Shengelia announced he was prematurely terminating his contract with CSKA Moscow "in protest against Russia's invasion of Ukraine".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Citing the club's historical links to the Red Army, Shengelia said: "I do not consider it possible to continue playing for the Russian army club".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Liza Peskova, the daughter of Putin's spokesman Dmitry Peskov, shared an image of the "No to war" hashtag on her Instagram story but then quickly deleted it and criticized the protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Russia's richest billionaire, Mikhail Fridman, called for the "bloodshed to end".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] "It is terrible that Ukrainians and Russians are dying, people are suffering hardships, the economy is collapsing.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] By 27 February, several prominent Russian public figures living in exile had organized the Anti-War Committee of Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Mikhail Shishkin, winner of the 2000 Russian Booker Prize, wrote on *The Guardian* that "Putin is committing monstrous crimes in the name of my people, my country, and me" and saying that "in Putin's Russia it's impossible to breathe.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Actor Danila Kozlovsky posted several Instagram posts condemning the war, sharing an image of a crying refugee and using the "*Нет войне!*"-hashtag.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In a post on 27 February, Kozlovsky admitted to and apologized for his indifference to Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Timur Bekmambetov, director of hits such as *Night Watch*, condemned the invasion in an interview with Deadline.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Unconfirmed reports states that Bekmambetov (who is based in Los Angeles) and his family had cut ties with Russia completely, following the sale his production company Bazelevs Company.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 21 March, rock musician Zemfira released an anti-war music video to her 2017 song "Don't Shoot", while also removing all of her other songs from her YouTube channel.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The video contained footage of Russia's military assault on Ukraine and of anti-war protests in Moscow.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In May 2022, rock singer Yuri Shevchuk was prosecuted after speaking out against Putin and the war in Ukraine at a concert in Ufa.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] He said that "people of Ukraine are being murdered" and "our boys are dying over there" due to "some Napoleonic plans of another Caesar of ours".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] In October 2022, Russian actor Artur Smolyaninov was charged for "discrediting" the Russian military – that was after his anti-war statements and after he had left Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] He commented; "The laws of this state do not exist for me.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] The founders of the "Immortal Regiment" commemoration movement, in which ordinary Russians carry photographs of veteran family members in marches around Russia held annually to mark WWII Victory Day on 9 May, addressed Vladimir Putin in a statement, asking him to "stop the bloodshed".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Svetlana Golub, head of the Union of the Committees of Soldiers' Mothers of Russia told The Guardian that "Wars always lead to deaths.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] From the many conversations I have been sent between soldiers and their families, I believe many Russians have already died...
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] Conflicts always mean lots of suffering.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p01] On 3 March, the multinational company Lukoil, the second largest company in Russia after Gazprom, called for a ceasefire and diplomatic means to solve the conflict.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A spokesperson for the United Nations condemned the "arbitrary arrests" of protesters, and called for their immediate release.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russia's interior ministry justified the arrests due to the "coronavirus restrictions, including on public events" that remained in place.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian authorities warned Russians of legal repercussions for joining anti-war protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Works by Russian authors critical of the war (ex.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Vladimir Sorokin, Dmitry Bykov, Boris Akunin) have been subject to censorship in the form of being withdrawn from many Russian bookstores.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 1 March, the Moscow radio station Echo of Moscow, as well as the independent channel TV Rain, was forced off air for having aired opposition to the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] After completing their final broadcast, TV Rain put on a loop of *Swan Lake*, echoing the efforts of Soviet authorities to bury bad news, including the 1991 attempted coup d'état as the USSR was breaking up.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 4 March, the Russian parliament passed a law aimed at stifling reporting on and opposition to the war which punishes citizens with up to 15 years in jail for spreading "fake information" about the Russian military and its operations.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] This law also makes it illegal "to make calls against the use of Russian troops to protect the interests of Russia" or "for discrediting such use" with a penalty possible of up to three years in prison.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The same provision applies to calls for sanctions against Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] This law effectively criminalizes any public opposition to or independent news reporting about the war against Ukraine and could make it a crime to simply call the war a "war" — the Kremlin says it is a "special military operation" — on social media or in a news article or broadcast.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Later that day, Putin signed the bill into law; he also signed into law a bill that would allow fines or prison sentences of up to 3 years for those calling for sanctions.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Mediazona defiantly promised to continue, providing tips to evade censorship.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 11 March, Roskomnadzor blocked the websites of Amnesty International as well as that of Russian election monitoring group Golos.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to the news website Agentstvo, over 150 journalists left Russia by 7 March since Putin signed the bill into law.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 16 March, Russian socialite and food blogger Veronika Belotserkovskaya became the first individual charged under Russia's new "false information" law.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 25 March, Russian journalist Izabella Yevloyeva was charged under the "fakes law" after sharing a post on social media that described the "Z" symbol as being "synonymous with aggression, death, pain and shameless manipulation".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Sergei Klokov, a Moscow policeman with Ukrainian roots, who is originally from Bucha, Kyiv Oblast, was arrested after he told colleagues what he had heard from his father and Ukrainian family friends about the Russian invasion.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to OVD-Info, over 400 people were detained or fined by April under the laws prohibiting "fake" information about the military.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The use of fake messages was claimed to have been used by Russian authorities by at least one Russian anti-war protester.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] He claimed that shortly after he was released from detention strange anti-war messages appeared on his phone, and had feared the messages were an attempt to incriminate him before he could leave the country.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] More than 2,000 people were detained or fined by May 2022 under the laws prohibiting "fake" information about the military.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] By early June, 53 criminal cases had been opened.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In July 2022, Alexei Gorinov, a member of the Krasnoselsky district council in Moscow, was sentenced to seven years in prison after making anti-war comments at a council meeting in March, including stating that Russia was waging a war of aggression against Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Lawyer Pavel Chikov said that this was the first jail term under the new law.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In August 2022, the former mayor of Yekaterinburg, Yevgeny Roizman, was detained by police where he said he was being charged with "discrediting" the military.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Roizman was previously fined three times under the same law.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to OVD-Info, the total number of people detained across Russia after six months is around 16,500, with over 3,800 being charged with offenses that carry fines, and at least 224 facing criminal prosecution.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In December 2022, a Moscow court sentenced opposition politician Ilya Yashin to eight years and six months imprisonment for his statements about the circumstances of the killings in Bucha on charges of "spreading false information" about the armed forces.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] His punishment was the harshest given under the new laws.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] OVD-Info said that over 380 others were on trial for similar charges.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In January 2023, an opposition deputy of the Saint Petersburg Legislative Assembly, Boris Vishnevskiy, as well as a former deputy, Maxim Reznik, were charged with discrediting the armed forces over "materials about the city of Bucha" and a "large number of killed civilians".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In March 2023, a new law was signed establishing criminal liability for "discrediting" and spreading "fakes" against mercenaries and volunteers fighting for Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Article 280.3 ("discrediting") was amended to increase the maximum prison term from five years to seven years.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Article 207.3 ("fakes") was amended to increase terms from three years to five years under the first part of the law, with the second and third parts remaining unchanged, at 10 and 15 years, respectively.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty has reported that students in some universities have been threatened with expulsion over acts of anti-war protest.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In early March, the student union of Saint Petersburg State University reported that the university has expelled at least 13 students for taking part in anti-war protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A number of anti-war activists and independent journalists in Russia have had their homes targeted with vandalism since the beginning of the invasion, including having manure and messages calling them traitors left outside their doors.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The Z symbol, which has achieved prominence in Russian popular culture as a symbol of support for the war, in part through state promotion of the symbol, has also been used to graffiti the homes of several anti-war activists.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to *The Moscow Times*, Russian authorities and pro-government figures have actively encouraged reporting other citizens, including friends and family, for "anti-Russian" activities including anti-war statements.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian NGO OVD-Info reported that it had confirmed at least 30 cases of protesters being beaten by police on the weekend of 5–6 March, as well as several cases of arrested protesters being tortured in detention, while saying that "it is likely that this number is much higher.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Mediazona has further reported that women who have been arrested have been subjected to threats of sexual violence, that arrested gender-non-conforming protesters have been ridiculed, and that police sprayed some detainees in the face with antiseptic solutions.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A number of people affiliated with the Russian government have spoken out against the protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Putin's press secretary, Dmitry Peskov, stated that "now is not the time to be divided.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Chairman of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin denounced Russians who oppose the war as "traitors".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] On 16 March 2022, Russian President Vladimir Putin issued a warning to Russian "traitors" who he said the West wanted to use as a "fifth column" to destroy Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Russian authorities encouraged Russians to report their friends, colleagues and family members to the police for expressing opposition to the war in Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Since the beginning of the invasion, more than 300,000 Russians have fled the country, particularly citizens who are opposed to the war, in response to increasing repression and rumours of conscription and martial law.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Journalist Boris Grozovski published a Facebook post saying that "We are not tourists, dear citizens of Georgia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Personally, I was wanted by the police in Russia for distributing anti-war petitions...
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] We ran not from bullets, bombs and missiles, but from prison.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Bolshoi Theater ballerina Olga Smirnova left Russia to continue her career in the Netherlands in protest of the war.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] By early April, an estimated 100,000 Russians had fled Russia to Georgia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] After three weeks of war, around 14,000 were said to have left for Turkey.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Tens of thousands went to Armenia; by 24 May an estimated 108,000 Russian citizens having fled to the country, or Nordic states such as Finland.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Thousands are said to have gone to Uzbekistan.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A state-run poll published on 28 February by the Russian Public Opinion Research Center claimed that 68% of Russians supported the "special military operation", 22% opposed, and 10% found it difficult to answer.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Later on, a series of four online polls by Alexei Navalny's Anti-Corruption Foundation claimed to show sentiment rapidly shifting among Moscow residents.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Between 25 February and 3 March, those blaming Russia for the war increased from 14% to 36%, with 79% now in favour of stopping the conflict and engaging in peace negotiation.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The proportion of respondents who considered Russia an "aggressor" increased from 29% to 53%, while the share of those considering Russia a "peace-maker" fell by half from 25% to 12%.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] From 26 to 28 February 2022, a survey conducted by the independent research group Russian Field found that 58.8% of respondents supported the "special military operation" in Ukraine.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] According to the poll, in the group of 18-to-24-year-olds, only 29% supported the "special military operation".
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A poll by the independent Levada Center published on 30 March saw Putin's approval rating jump from 71% in February to 83% in March.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] A study by researchers affiliated with the London School of Economics found that stated support for the war among Russians dropped from 68% to 53% when asked indirectly about the invasion in polls.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Many respondents do not want to answer pollsters' questions for fear of negative consequences.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In March 2022, when a Russian opposition politician Maxim Katz and a group of Russian researchers commissioned a poll on Russians' attitudes toward the war in Ukraine, 29,400 of the 31,000 people they called refused to answer after hearing the subject matter in question.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Many have been planned through personal networks and social media posts.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In some cases, opponents of the war have simply travelled to their nearest city centre in the hope of finding like-minded citizens.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Several commentators have noted the significant presence of youth in the anti-war protests in Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Commentators have also noted the significant role of women in the protests.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] One reason many Russians have supported the "special military operation" in Ukraine has to do with the propaganda and disinformation being sown by the Kremlin.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Some observers noted what they described as a "generational struggle" among Russians over perception of the war, with younger Russians more likely opposed to the war and older Russians more likely to accept the narrative presented by state-controlled media in Russia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The effect of international sanctions and condemnation of the war at domestic anti-war protests has been debated.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] In early March 2022, Kremlinologist Lilia Shevtsova stated that "the 'Crimea effect' is vanishing.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] The war in Ukraine creates 'our' casualties – this will have an impact.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] Moreover, in 2008 and 2014, the wars were relatively short and they ended with 'our' victory.
[src:ahimsa/2022-anti-war-protests-in-russia-p02] As of December 2023, support for Putin's war in Ukraine among Russians hit an all-time low.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] With the beginning of mobilization in Russia in September 2022 during the Russo-Ukrainian war, anti-war and anti-mobilization protests broke out in the Russian Far East, mostly performed by women.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Former Mongolian President Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj protested against usage of ethnic minorities such as the Buryats, Tuvans, and Kalmyks as cannon fodder, and invited them to Mongolia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] The Tuvans belong to Turkic peoples but are also regarded in Mongolia as one of the Uriankhai peoples.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Women protested in Ordzhonikidze Square, in Yakutsk.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Some elderly men were conscripted by mistake.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Small groups protested in Ulan-Ude under handwritten signs "No war!
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] No mobilization!" and "Our husbands, fathers and brothers don’t want to kill other husbands and fathers." The Free Buryatia Foundation collects appeals for help from families of mobilised men.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] According to Alexandra Garmazhapova, president of the foundation, some local people try to go to Mongolia.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Marina Salomatova, a member of the "Transbaikal Civil Solidarity", has been arrested in Chita, Zabaykalsky Krai.
[src:ahimsa/2022-far-eastern-protests] Women protested against mobilization in Kyzyl, 20 of them were arrested.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] To carry out an order received in his youth from his spiritual teacher to spread "Krishna consciousness" in English, he journeyed from Kolkata to New York City in 1965 at the age of 69, on a cargo ship with little more than a few trunks of books.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He knew no one in America, but he chanted Hare Krishna in a park in New York City, gave classes, and in 1966, with the help of some early students, established the International Society for Krishna Consciousness (ISKCON), which now has centers around the world.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He taught a path in which one aims at realizing oneself to be an eternal spiritual being, distinct from one's temporary material body, and seeks to revive one's dormant relationship with the supreme living being, known by the Sanskrit name Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] One does this through various practices, especially through hearing about Krishna from standard texts, chanting mantras consisting of names of Krishna, and adopting a life of devotional service to Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] As part of these practices, Prabhupada required that his initiated students strictly refrain from non-vegetarian food (such as meat, fish, or eggs), gambling, intoxicants (including coffee, tea, or cigarettes), and extramarital sex.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In contrast to earlier Indian teachers who promoted the idea of an impersonal ultimate truth in the West, he taught that the Absolute is ultimately personal.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He held that the duty of a guru was to convey intact the message of Krishna as found in core spiritual texts such as the *Bhagavad Gita*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In all, he wrote more than eighty books.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In the late 1970s and the 1980s, ISKCON came to be labelled a destructive cult by critics in America and some European countries.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Although scholars and courts rejected claims of cultic brainwashing and recognized ISKCON as representing an authentic branch of Hinduism, the "cult" label and image have persisted in some places.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Some of Prabhupada's views or statements have been perceived as racist towards Black people, discriminatory against lower castes, or misogynistic.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Decades after his death, Prabhupada's teachings and the Society he established continue to be influential, with some scholars and Indian political leaders calling him one of the most successful propagators of Hinduism abroad.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Abhay Charan De was born into a Bengali Hindu Banik Family in Calcutta (now Kolkata), India, on 1 September 1896, the day after Janmashtami (the birth anniversary of Krishna).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] His parents, Gour Mohan De and Rajani De, named him Abhay Charan, meaning "one who is fearless, having taken shelter of Lord Krishna's lotus feet".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Following Indian tradition, Abhay's father invited an astrologer, who predicted that at the age of seventy, Abhay would cross the ocean, become a famous religious teacher, and open 108 temples around the world.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Abhay was raised in a religious family belonging to the Bengali.Kayastha His parents were Gaudiya Vaishnavas, or followers of Chaitanya Mahaprabhu, who taught that Krishna is the Supreme Personality and that pure love for Krishna is the highest attainment.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Gour Mohan was a middle-income merchant and had his own fabric and clothing store.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He was related to the rich and aristocratic Mullik mercantile family, who had been trading in gold and salt for centuries.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Opposite the De house was a temple of Radha-Krishna that for a century and a half had been supported by the Mullik family.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Every day, young Abhay, accompanied by his parents or servants, attended temple services.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] At the age of six, Abhay organized a likeness of the "chariot festival", or Ratha-yatra, an annual *Vaishnava* festival in the city of Puri, Odisha.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] For this purpose, Abhay persuaded his father to obtain for him a scaled-down copy of the massive chariot on which the form of Jagannatha (Krishna as "Lord of the universe") rides in procession in Puri.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Decades later, after going to America, Abhay would bring Ratha-yatra festivals to the West.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Though Abhay's mother wanted him to go to London to study law, his father rejected the idea, fearing Abhay would be negatively influenced by Western society and acquire bad habits.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1916, Abhay began his studies at the Scottish Church College, a prestigious school in Calcutta founded by Alexander Duff, a Christian missionary.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1918, while in college, Abhay, as arranged by his father, married Radharani Datta, also from an aristocratic family.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] They had five children over the course of their marriage.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After graduation from college, Abhay began a career in pharmaceuticals and later opened his own pharmaceutical company in Allahabad.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Abhay grew up while India was under British rule, and like many other youth of his age he was attracted to Mahatma Gandhi's non-cooperation movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1920, Abhay graduated from college with a specialization in English, philosophy, and economics.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He successfully passed the final exams, but as a sign of opposition to British rule he refused to take part in the graduation ceremony and receive a diploma.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1922, while still in college, Abhay was persuaded by a friend, Narendranath Mullik, to meet with Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati (1874–1937), a Vaishnava scholar and teacher and the founder of the Gaudiya Math, a spiritual institution for spreading the teachings of Chaitanya Mahaprabhu.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The word *math* denotes a monastic or missionary center.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktisiddhanta was continuing the work of his father, Bhaktivinoda Thakur (1838–1914), who regarded Chaitanya's teachings as the highest form of theism, intended not for any one religion or nation but for all of humanity.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] When the meeting took place, Bhaktisiddhanta said to Abhay, "You are an educated young man.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Convinced by Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati, Abhay accepted the instruction to spread the message of Chaitanya in English, and it was in pursuing this order from Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati that he later traveled to New York.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Many years later he recalled: "I immediately accepted him as spiritual master.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After meeting Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati in 1922, Abhay had little contact with the Gaudiya Math until 1928, when *sannyasis* (renounced, itinerant preachers) from the Math came to open a center in Allahabad, where Abhay and his family were living.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Abhay became a regular visitor, contributed funds, and brought important people to the lectures of the Math's *sannyasis*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1932, he visited Bhaktisiddhanta in the holy town of Vrindavan, and in 1933, when Bhaktisiddhanta came to Allahabad to lay the cornerstone for a new temple, Abhay received *diksha* (spiritual initiation) from him and was given the name Abhay Charanaravinda.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Over the next three years, whenever Abhay was able to visit Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati in Calcutta or Vrindavan, he would carefully listen to his spiritual master.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1935, Abhay moved for business reasons to Bombay; then, in 1937, he moved back to Calcutta.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In both places, he assisted other members of the Gaudiya Math by donating money, leading *kirtans*, lecturing, writing, and bringing others to the Math.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] At the end of 1936, he visited Vrindavan, where he again met Bhaktisiddhanta, who told him, "If you ever get money, print books", an instruction that would inform his life's work.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Two weeks before his death on 1 January 1937, Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati wrote a letter to Abhay urging him to teach Gaudiya Vaishnavism in English.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After Bhaktisiddhanta died, the unified mission of the Gaudiya Math broke down as a battle for power broke out between his senior disciples.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Although Abhay continued to serve with other disciples of his spiritual master and wrote articles for their publications, he kept clear of the political struggles.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1939, elders in the Gaudiya community honored Abhay Charanaravinda (A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In the title, *bhakti* means "devotion", and *vedanta* means "the culmination of Vedic knowledge".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Thus the honorary title acknowledged his scholarship and devotion.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In an effort to fulfill the order of his guru, in 1944, A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta began publishing *Back to Godhead*, an English fortnightly magazine presenting the teachings of Chaitanya Mahaprabhu.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He single-handedly wrote, edited, financed, published, and distributed the magazine, which is still published and distributed by his followers.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta accepted the *vanaprastha ashram* (the traditional retired order of life), and went to live in Vrindavan, regarded as the site of Krishna's *Lila* (divine pastimes), although he occasionally commuted to Delhi.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In Mathura, adjoining Vrindavan, he wrote for and edited the *Gauḍīya Patrikā* magazine published by his godbrother Bhakti Prajnan Keshava.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta attempted to set up organized spiritual activities in the central Indian city of Jhansi, where he started "The League of Devotees", only to see the organization collapse two years later.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] On 17 September 1959, prompted by a dream of Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati calling on him to accept *sannyasa* (renounced order of life), A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta formally entered *sannyasa asrama* from Bhakti Prajnan Keshava at his Keshavaji Gaudiya Math in Mathura and was given the name Bhaktivedanta Swami.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Wishing to preserve the initiatory name given him by Bhaktisiddhanta, as a sign of humility and connection to his spiritual master he kept the initials "A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] C." before his *sannyasa* name, becoming A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] From 1962 to 1965, Bhaktivedanta Swami stayed in Vrindavan at the Radha-Damodar temple.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] There he began the task of translating from Sanskrit into English and commenting on the 1800-verse *Srimad-Bhagavatam* (Bhagavata Purana), the foundational text of Gaudiya Vaishnavism.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] With great effort and struggle, he finally succeeded to translate, produce, raise funds for, and print the first of its twelve cantos, in three volumes.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] , for five days his diary has no entries.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He then writes, "Passed over a great crisis on the struggle for life and death".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After accepting *sannyasa*, Bhaktivedanta Swami began planning to travel to America to fulfill his spiritual master's desire to spread Chaitanya's teachings in the West.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] To leave India, Bhaktivedanta Swami had many hurdles to overcome.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He needed a sponsor in America, official approvals in India, and a ticket for his travel.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After significant difficulties he managed to secure the needed sponsorship and approvals.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He then approached one of his well-wishers, Sumati Morarjee, the head of the Scindia Steam Navigation Company, to ask for free passage to America on one of her cargo ships.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Because of his age, she at first tried to dissuade him.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Finally she relented and granted him a ticket on a freighter, the *Jaladuta.* Bhaktivedanta Swami began the 35-day journey to America on 13 August 1965, at the age of 69.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta took with him little more than a suitcase, an umbrella, some dry cereal, forty Indian rupees (about seven US dollars), and two hundred three-volume sets of his translation of the first canto of *Srimad-Bhagavatam*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After surviving two heart attacks during his maritime journey, Bhaktivedanta Swami finally arrived at the Boston Harbor on 17 September 1965, and then continued on to New York City.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta Swami had no support or acquaintances in the United States except the Agarwals, an Indian-American family, who, although strangers to him, had agreed to sponsor his visa.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Upon reaching New York, he took a bus to the town of Butler, Pennsylvania, where the Agarwals lived.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In Butler he delivered lectures to different groups at venues such as the local YMCA.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After a month in Butler, he returned by bus to New York City.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After he and his followers held Hare Krishna kirtan one Sunday under a tree in nearby Tompkins Square Park, *The New York Times* reported the event: "Swami's Flock Chants in Park to Find Ecstasy; 50 Followers Clap and Sway to Hypnotic Music at East Side Ceremony".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He slowly gained a following, mainly from young people of the 1960s counterculture.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] New initiates also vowed to daily chant sixteen meditative "rounds" of the Hare Krishna 'mantra' (that is, to complete sixteen circuits of chanting the mantra on a 108-bead strand).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] During the first year in New York, he initiated nineteen people.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In July 1966, he incorporated the International Society for Krishna Consciousness (ISKCON).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In December 1966, he made a recording of Krishna kirtan (along with a brief explanatory talk) that took the form of an album entitled *Krishna Consciousness*, released under the "Happening" record label.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The record helped the early spread of what he called "the Hare Krishna movement".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] With his small band of followers in a little storefront, he was already sharing a vision of spreading "Krishna consciousness" around the world.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He asked them to help, for example, by typing his manuscripts for the second canto of the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] After he completed his *Bhagavad-gita As It Is* (by mid-January 1967), he asked a new disciple to find a publisher for it.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Bhaktivedanta Swami personally taught his first followers to spread Krishna's message, prepare food to offer to Krishna, collect donations, and chant the Hare Krishna *maha-mantra* ("great mantra") on the streets.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1967, Bhaktivedanta Swami established a second center, in San Francisco.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The opening of the temple in the heart of the booming hippie community of Haight-Ashbury attracted many new adherents and was a turning point in his movement's history, marking the beginning of rapid growth.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] To gain attention and raise funds, his disciples organized a two-hour concert with kirtan led by Bhaktivedanta Swami and rock performances by the Grateful Dead and other famous rock groups of the day.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] This "Mantra Rock Dance", held at the popular Avalon Ballroom, attracted some three thousand people and brought attention to the local Hare Krishna temple.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] One commentator dubbed it the "ultimate high of that era".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Later that year, Bhaktivedanta Swami's followers organized San Francisco's first Ratha Yatra, the festival he had celebrated as a child in imitation of the massive parade held annually in the Indian city of Puri.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] For this first San Francisco version, a flatbed truck with four pillars holding a canopy took the place of Puri's three huge ornate wooden vehicles.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He would later establish this annual festival in major cities around the world, with big vehicles —"chariots" — and thousands of people taking part.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] At first, Bhaktivedanta Swami's followers referred to him as "the Swami" or "Swamiji".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] From mid-1968 onwards they called him "Prabhupada", a respectful epithet that "enjoys currency with devotees and an increasing number of scholars".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1968, Prabhupada asked three married couples among his disciples to open a temple in London, England.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Following his instructions, the disciples, dressed in their robes and *saris*, began singing Hare Krishna regularly on London streets and at once attracted attention.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Soon newspapers carried headlines like "Krishna Chant Startles London" and "Happiness is Hare Krishna".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] A further breakthrough came in December 1969 when the disciples managed to meet with members of the rock band the Beatles, who were at the peak of their global fame.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Even before then, George Harrison and John Lennon had obtained a copy of the maha-mantra recording released by Prabhupada and his students in New York and had begun singing Hare Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In August 1969, Harrison produced a single of the Hare Krishna mantra, sung by the London disciples, and released it on Apple Records.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] For the recording, the disciples called themselves "The Radha Krishna Temple".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Harrison told a press conference convened by Apple that the Hare Krishna mantra was not a pop song but an ancient mantra that awakened spiritual bliss in the hearts of people listening to and repeating it.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Seventy thousand copies of the record sold on the first day.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] It rose to number 11 on the British charts, and Prabhupada's students performed live four times on the BBC's popular TV show *Top of the Pops*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Also in 1970, Harrison sponsored the publishing of the first volume of Prabhupada's book *Kṛṣṇa, the Supreme Personality of Godhead*, which related the activities of Krishna's life as told in the tenth canto of the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1973 Harrison donated a seventeen-acre estate known as Piggots Manor, fifteen miles northwest of London.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The Hare Krishna devotees converted this into a rural temple-ashram and renamed it Bhaktivedanta Manor in Prabhupada's honor.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1970, Prabhupada made the first of several visits to Kenya.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Although the disciples he had sent there had settled into doing spiritual programs for the local Indian people, Prabhupada insisted on doing programs meant for Africans.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] On one notable occasion in Nairobi, when he was scheduled to do a program at an Indian Radha-Krishna temple in a mainly African area downtown, he ordered the doors opened to invite the local residents.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Soon the hall was flooded with African people.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada told his local leaders that they should spread Krishna consciousness among the local African people.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada also later visited Mauritius and South Africa and sent his disciples to Nigeria and Zambia.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada's visit to Moscow from 20 to 25 June 1971 marked the beginning of Krishna consciousness in the Soviet Union.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] During his five days in Moscow, Prabhupada managed to meet only two Soviet citizens: Grigory Kotovsky, a professor of Indian and South Asian studies, and Anatoly Pinyaev, a twenty-three-year-old Muscovite.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Pinyaev, who went on to become the first Soviet Hare Krishna devotee, met Prabhupada through the son of an Indian diplomat stationed in Moscow.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada's assistant gave Pinyaev a copy of Prabhupada's *Bhagavad-gita*, which Pinyaev was able to translate into Russian, copy, and then distribute underground in the Soviet Union.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Pinyaev showed a great interest in Gaudiya Vaishnavism, accepted initiation from Prabhupada, and did much to ignite interest in Krishna consciousness in the Soviet Union.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Pinyaev was later imprisoned in Smolensk Special Psychiatric Hospital and forcibly treated with drugs for his practice of Krishna consciousness.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Having achieved some success in the West, in 1970 Prabhupada directed his attention especially to India, with the hope of turning India back toward its original spiritual sensibilities.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] By that time, Prabhupada saw that India had set a course towards Europeanization and sought to imitate the West.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Therefore, the appearance on Indian soil of American and European Hare Krishna devotees who had rejected Western materialism and embraced Indian spiritual culture "caused nothing less than a sensation among the modernizing (i.e.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Westernizing) Indians, planting seeds for an authentic religious revival there".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] By the early 1970s, Prabhupada had established his movement's American headquarters in Los Angeles and its world headquarters in Mayapur.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In Latin America, Prabhupada visited Mexico and Venezuela.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In Asia he visited Hong Kong, Japan, Malaysia, Indonesia, and the Philippines.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He also spent time in Australia, New Zealand, and Fiji.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Among the places he sent disciples to spread Krishna consciousness was China.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Early in the movement, Prabhupada had guided his students personally, but later, as the movement rapidly expanded, he relied more on letters and his secretaries.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] By giving his students instructions, advice, and encouragement, he ensured a "strong paternal presence" in their lives.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He wrote more than six thousand letters, many now collected and kept in the Bhaktivedanta Archives.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Besides receiving reports of accomplishments, he also had to deal through correspondence with almost daily setbacks, perplexities, quarrels, and failures.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He tried to correct or resolve these as much as he could and kept on advancing his movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Wherever he was, he took an hour-long early-morning walk, which became a time for disciples to ask questions and receive personal guidance.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] On returning from his walk, he lectured daily on the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*, often reading from the portion of the manuscript he was working on.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Every afternoon he met with disciples or with dignitaries and leaders from various parts of his mission.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Traveling constantly to lecture and tend to his disciples, Prabhupada circled the world fourteen times in ten years.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He opened more than one hundred temples and dozens of farm communities and restaurants, as well as *gurukulas* (boarding schools) for ISKCON's children.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He initiated nearly five thousand disciples.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] On 14 November 1977, at the age of 81, after a long illness, Prabhupada died in his room at the Krishna Balaram Mandir, the temple he had established in Vrindavan, India.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] His burial site is located in the courtyard of the temple beneath a *samadhi* (memorial shrine) built by his followers.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1970, Prabhupada established a Governing Body Commission (GBC), then consisting of twelve leading disciples, to oversee ISKCON's activities around the world and to serve as ISKCON's ultimate managing authority.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In 1977, four months before his death, he appointed eleven senior disciples to perform spiritual initiations on his behalf while he was ill.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Despite the measures Prabhupada took to organize the management of his movement, his death caused a crisis of authority in ISKCON that destabilized the organization and became a turning point in its development.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The succession process was beset by conflicts, with disagreements persisting for decades.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Nonetheless, by 2023 nearly one hundred disciples and grand-disciples in succession from Prabhupada were serving as initiating gurus in his branch of the Gaudiya Vaishnava lineage.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Within Eastern systems, spiritual lineages are integral to each tradition, and a teacher is mandated to maintain theological fidelity by transmitting knowledge as given in the lineage.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada comes in the Brahma-Madhva-Gaudiya lineage, which traces back to Chaitanya Mahaprabhu and Madhvacharya, and further back, its teachings say, to the beginnings of creation.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] This lineage (*sampradaya*) follows such texts as *Srimad-Bhagavatam*, the *Bhagavad-gita*, and the writings of Chaitanya's disciples and their followers.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada's extensive commentaries on the sacred texts follow those of Bhaktisiddhanta, Bhaktivinoda, and other traditional teachers, such as Baladeva Vidyabhushana, Vishvanatha Chakravarti, Jiva Goswami, Madhvacharya, and Ramanujacharya.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In accordance with the teachings of the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*, Prabhupada taught that the supreme truth, or Absolute Truth, is the one unlimited, undivided spiritual entity that is the source of all.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] That Absolute Truth, he taught, is realized in three phases: as *Brahman* (all-pervading impersonal oneness), as *Paramatma* (the aspect of God present within the heart of every living being), and as *Bhagavan*, the Supreme Personality of Godhead.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Though the Absolute Truth is one, he taught, that one Absolute is progressively realized in these three features according to one's level of spiritual advancement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In the initial stage the Absolute is realized as Brahman, in a more advanced stage as Paramatma, and at the most advanced stage as *Bhagavan*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*, and so in Prabhupada's teachings, Krishna is seen as the original and supreme manifestation of Bhagavan – in Sanskrit, *svayam-bhagavan*, or the Supreme Personality of Godhead Himself.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] No one is equal to or greater than Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Brahman and Paramatma are partial realizations of Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The various Vishnu forms, such as Rama and Narasimha, are "nondifferent" from Krishna; they are the same Personality of Godhead, appearing in different roles.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The form of Krishna is the original and the most complete form.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In the Hindu pantheon, he taught the gods other than the Vishnu forms are demigods — that is, assistants of the Supreme Personality of Godhead.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] If the Absolute Truth is one, this raises the question of how diversity can exist.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] If, as the *Upanishads* say, there is only the Absolute Truth and nothing else, we need some way to account for the existence of living beings, with all their differences, and the world, with all its many colors, forms, sounds, aromas, and so on.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada responds by referencing a statement from the *Upanishads* that the Absolute Truth has varied energies.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] As a fire located in one place gives off heat and light throughout a room, the Absolute Truth fills the world with every sort of variety.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada taught Chaitanya's doctrine of *achintya bheda-abheda-tattva*, in which everything is seen as simultaneously, inconceivably one with the Absolute — that is, with Krishna — and yet different.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] By way of analogy, Prabhupada gives the example that heat is in one sense identical with the fire from which it emerges and yet the two are different — when sitting in a fire's warmth, we are not burning in the fire itself.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] This "oneness and difference" accounts for the oneness of an Absolute Truth that includes limitless varieties.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Among Krishna's energies, Prabhupada taught, the ingredients of this world collectively belong to Krishna's "inferior energy" — inferior in that, being inert matter, it lacks consciousness.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] But superior to inert matter are the conscious living beings (*jivas*) that belong to Krishna's "superior energy".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Because the living beings belong to Krishna's "superior energy", Prabhupada taught, they share in Krishna's divine qualities, including knowledge, bliss, and eternality (*sat*, *cit*, and *ananda*).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] But because of contact with the "inferior energy" since time immemorial, the divine nature of the living beings has been covered, and subjecting the living beings in this world to ignorance, suffering, and repeated birth and death.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Living beings struggle against birth and death, disease, and old age in each life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] While trying to control and enjoy the resources of nature, living beings increasingly suffer from entanglement in nature's complexities.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] As spiritual beings belonging to the "superior energy", the living beings are different from their material bodies: the body may be male or female, young or old, white or black, American or Indian, but the living being within the body is beyond what he called these "material designations".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada phrased this understanding in a maxim he often used: "I am not this body".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] He taught that when we falsely identify with these bodies, we are under the influence of Maya, or illusion.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Only when this illusion is dispelled can the soul become liberated from material existence.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada taught that living beings can be freed from illusion and from their entire material predicament by recognizing that they are tiny but eternal parts of Krishna and that their natural engagement lies in serving Krishna, just as a hand serves the body.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Dormant within every living being, Prabhupada taught, is an eternal loving relationship with that Absolute, or Krishna, and when that loving relationship is revived, the living being resumes its natural eternal and joyful life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] This eternal service in devotion to Krishna, rendered by one freed from all material designation, is called *bhakti*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] One can begin practicing *bhakti*, Prabhupada taught, even while in the earliest stages of spiritual life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In this way, *bhakti* is both the end and how to achieve it.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] As a spiritual practice, *bhakti* is a powerful, transformative process that purifies the soul and enables it to see God directly.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada crusaded against what he called "impersonalism"—the idea that the Supreme has no form, qualities, activities, or personal attributes.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In this way, he stood opposed to the teachings of Shankara (AD 788–820), who held that everything except Brahman is illusory, including the soul, the world, and God.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] But prominent Vaishnava philosophers from the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, like Madhva and Ramanuja, had opposed Shankara's views with personalistic understandings of Vedanta.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Those teachers presented strong philosophical arguments criticizing Shankara's "illusionism" (*mayavada*), his view that personal individuality, indeed all individuality, is illusory.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Philosophers in the Gaudiya line such as, in the sixteenth century, Jiva Goswami had continued to argue formidably against impersonalism, which they regarded as *the* essential metaphysical misconception".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] So Prabhupada strongly opposed impersonalistic views wherever he encountered them and asserted the eternal personal existence of the Absolute and of all living beings.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Where Buddhism shares ground with Shankara's views by teaching that ultimately personality disintegrates, leaving nothing but a void *nirvana*, Buddhism too came in for Prabhupada's strong personalistic critique.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada taught that society should ideally be organized in such a way that people have specific duties according to their occupation (*varna*) and stage of life (*ashrama*).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The four *varnas* are intellectual work; administrative and military work; agriculture and business; and ordinary labor and assistance.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The four *ashramas* are student life, married life, retired life, and renounced life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In accordance with the *Bhagavad-gita* and in opposition to the modern Hindu caste system, Prabhupada taught that one's *varna*, or occupational standing, should be understood in terms of one's qualities and the work one actually does, not by one's birth.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Moreover, devotional qualifications always supersede material ones.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Following Chaitanya, who challenged the caste system and undercut hierarchical power structures, Prabhupada taught that anyone could take to the practice of *bhakti-yoga* and become self-realized through the chanting of God's holy names, as found in the *Hare Krishna maha-mantra*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada also emphasized the importance of self-sufficient farming communities as places where one could live simply and cultivate Krishna consciousness.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] *Krishna kirtan*, he had taught, can be done by anyone, anywhere, at any time, and without hard-and-fast rules.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Because the names of Krishna are "transcendental sounds", identical with Krishna Himself, the chanting is spiritually uplifting.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] When Prabhupada began his efforts to spread Krishna consciousness in the United States, he held *kirtans* in a Bowery loft, in his early storefront temples, in Tompkins Square Park in New York and Golden Gate Park in San Francisco, and wherever else he went.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Following Prabhupada, his disciples soon began holding *kirtans* regularly in streets, parks, temples, and other venues in major cities in North America and Europe and then in Latin America, Australia, Africa, and Asia.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Because of Hare Krishna *kirtan*, Prabhupada's movement itself came to be known simply as "Hare Krishna" and its followers as "Hare Krishnas".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Theologically speaking, the term *sankirtana* can extend from the public chanting of Hare Krishna to the distribution of books spoken by or about Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada therefore gave great importance to such distribution.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada's tradition constantly makes the point that "association with saints inspires saintliness, association with devotees inspires devotion.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] The association of genuine devotees can exert a powerful effect upon one's consciousness".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] And so when Prabhupada incorporated ISKCON, its founding document included as one of the Society's purposes "To bring the members of the Society together with each other and nearer to Krishna".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] New initiates also vowed to daily chant sixteen meditative "rounds" of the *Hare Krishna mantra* (that is, to complete sixteen circuits of chanting the mantra on a 108-bead strand).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] For at least the last millennium, the *Srimad-Bhagavatam* has been "by far the most important work in the Krishna tradition" and "the scripture *par excellence* of the Krishnaite schools".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] It is sometimes described as "the ripened fruit of the Vedic tree".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Accordingly, Prabhupada instituted daily classes on the *Bhagavatam* in all his centers, and he spoke on *Bhagavatam* daily, wherever he went.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] In accordance with Vaishnava teachings, Prabhupada introduced the worship of Krishna in the form of a *murti*: figures cast in metal or carved in stone or wood to match descriptions of Krishna given in Vaishnava texts.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada taught that because Krishna is personally present as the Deity (the term Prabhupada used for such a form), worshiping the Deity helps one develop loving exchanges with Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada installed deities in ISKCON temples worldwide.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Food prepared and offered to the Deity of Krishna with devotion becomes sanctified as *krishna-prasadam* ("mercy of Krishna").
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada taught that eating only *prasadam* purifies one's existence and helps one develop in *bhakti*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] From the beginning of his mission, Prabhupada distributed *prasadam* to visitors and soon made it into the movement's primary outreach vehicle.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] A weekly *prasadam* feast for the public has always been a program at all of ISKCON centers.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada wrote, "The Hare Krishna Movement is based on the principle: chant Hare Krishna mantra at every moment, both inside and outside of the temples, and, as far as possible, distribute prasadam".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada's predecessors such as Rupa Goswami had taught the value of living in Vrindavan (sometimes spelled "Vrindaban"), the sacred town between Agra and New Delhi that is held to be the site of Krishna's rural "pastimes" on earth and therefore conducive to constant remembrance of Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Prabhupada accordingly brought his disciples on pilgrimage to Vrindavan, and there, he established the Krishna-Balaram temple.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] Yet with a broader outlook, he wrote one disciple, "[W]herever you remain, if you are fully absorbed in your transcendental work in Krishna consciousness, that place is eternally Vrindaban.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p01] It is the consciousness that creates Vrindaban".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati, who had specifically encouraged writing and publishing, at one meeting told Prabhupada: If you ever get money, print books.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] So regardless of how busy or sometimes unwell Prabhupada might have been, he remained focused on producing books.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada slept little, waking at 1:00 am every night to translate and comment on the *Srimad-Bhagavatam* and other texts.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] By 1970, he had translated the *Bhagavad-gita*, two cantos of the *Bhagavatam*, a summary study of its tenth canto, and a summary volume drawn from the expansive Caitanya-caritamrta.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Starting in 1970, his literary output slowed only slightly due to the demands of his expanding Hare Krishna movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] His task, as scholars have observed, was not merely to translate the text but to translate an entire tradition.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Hopkins says that by presenting in English such works as the *Bhagavatam* and *Caitanya-caritamrta*, Prabhupada made important texts accessible to the Western world that were simply not accessible before.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Hopkins says, "[W]hat few English translations there were of the *Bhagavata* *Purana* and *Caitanya-caritamrta* were barely adequate and very hard to get hold of".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada, Hopkins says, "made these and other texts available in a way that they never were before" and "made the tradition itself accessible to the West".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1966–67, Prabhupada wrote a translation and commentary on the *Bhagavad-gita* he entitled *Bhagavad-gita As It Is*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] It was first published by the Macmillan Company in 1968 in an abridged edition and later, in 1972, in full.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] For each verse he first gives the Sanskrit Devanagari script, then a roman transliteration and word-for-word gloss, followed by his translation and a commentary, or "purport".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Davis comments that this was "the first English translation of the *Gita* to supply an authentic interpretation from an Indian devotional tradition".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] It is "by far the most widely distributed of all English Gita translations".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2015 Davis wrote, "The Bhaktivedanta Book Trust estimates that twenty-three million copies of Prabhupada's translation have been sold, including the English original and secondary translations into fifty-six other languages".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] For Prabhupada, Davis says, "the essential fact about the *Bhagavad-gita* is its speaker.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The *Gita* contains the words of Krishna, and Krishna is the 'Supreme Personality of Godhead.'" In Prabhupada's view, other translations lack authority because the translators use them to express their own opinions rather than the message of Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In contrast, Prabhupada saw his task in presenting what Krishna wanted to say, and so he claimed to present the *Bhagavad-gita* "as it is".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] At once a sacred history, a theological treatise, and a philosophical text, the *Srimad-Bhagavatam* "stands out by reason of its literary excellence, the organization that it brings to its vast material, and the effect that it has had on later writers".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] It was this great work that Prabhupada, after taking *sannyasa*, set out to present in English, with, once again, the original Sanskrit text, its word-for-word meanings, a translation, and an in-depth commentary.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Also known as *Srimad-Bhagavata* *Purana*, *Bhagavata* *Purana*, or just the *Bhagavata* *Srimad-Bhagavatam* is a work of twelve books ("cantos" was the word Prabhupada used) comprising more than fourteen thousand verse couplets.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] "*Srimad*" means "beautiful" or "glorious".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada began his translation and commentary on the *Bhagavatam* after accepting *sannyasa* in 1959, and by 1965 he had completed and published the first canto.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He worked on translating the *Srimad-Bhagavatam* into English for the rest of his life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The cantos were published one by one, as he finished them.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He completed nine cantos and thirteen chapters of the tenth.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The rest of the *Bhagavatam* was completed by his disciples.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Considering his old age and the vast size of the *Bhagavatam*, Prabhupada knew he might not live to finish it.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] So in 1968 he undertook to present the *Bhagavatam*'s tenth canto — the essence of the work — in summary form as *Krsna, the Supreme Personality of Godhead*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] This summary study is "Prabhupada's own exposition of the story of Krishna as it is told in the Tenth Canto".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] It "laid out the account of Krishna from the *Bhagavata Purana* that provides the images and stories central to Krishna devotion".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada himself inspired artists among his disciples to provide the text with profuse full-color illustrations.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Such illustrations became a feature of nearly all his books.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] A related work is *Light of the Bhagavat*, written by Prabhupada in Vrindavan in 1961, before he went to the West, but published only after his death.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The book is a treatment of one chapter (chapter twenty) of the tenth canto.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada composed forty-eight commentaries for the chapter's verses.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The book is accordingly illustrated with forty-eight paintings.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1969 Prabhupada published, again in his full verse-by-verse format, his translation and commentary for the *Ishopanishad* — also known as the *Īśa Upaniṣad* or *Īśāvāsya Upaniṣad*, which in 1960 he had partially serialized in his *Back to Godhead* magazine.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The *Ishopanishad*, consisting of only eighteen *mantras*, is considered one of the principal *Upanishads*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In all indigenous collections of the *Upanishads*, the *Iśopaniṣad* comes first.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Its first verse, "highly regarded as a capsule of Vedic theology", presents a god-centered view of the universe.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The celebrated traditional commentator Shankara wrote, "One who is eager to rid himself of the suffering and delusion of saṁsāra, created by ignorance, and attain Supreme Bliss is entitled to read this *Upaniṣad*".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Begun in 1968, *The Nectar of Devotion* is a summary study of Rupa Goswami's *Bhakti-rasamrita-sindhu*, his "famous exposition of the principles of devotion".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Scholar-practitioner Shrivatsa Goswami has described *Bhakti-rasamrita-sindhu* as "a textbook of devotional practice, an exposition on the philosophy of devotion, and a study of devotional psychology".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] *The Nectar of Devotion* "gave access to Gaudiya Vaisnavism's most important theological treatise on devotion".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada completed his translation in 1974, within two years, and it was published in seventeen volumes, again with verse-by-verse text, transliteration, word meanings, translation and commentary.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He based his commentary on the Bengali commentaries of his predecessors Bhaktivinoda Thakura and Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Before Srila Prabhupada's translation, the work in English was simply unavailable.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After Prabhupada's edition came out, scholar J.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Bruce Long wrote, "The appearance of an English translation of Kṛṣṇadāsa Kavirāja Gosvāmī's *Śri Caitanya-caritāmṛta* by A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Bhaktivedānta, Founder-Ācārya of the International Society for Krishna Consciousness, is a cause for celebration among both scholars in Indian Studies and lay-people seeking to enrich their knowledge of Indian spirituality".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Several years earlier, in 1968, Prabhupada published *Teachings of Lord Caitanya*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The book offers a summary of selected portions of *Caitanya-caritamrita*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada also wrote a verse-by-verse commentated translation of Rupa Goswami's eleven-verse *Upadeshamrita*, one of Rupa Goswami's shortest works, which provides concise directions on how to carry out devotional service.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1972 Prabhupada founded the Bhaktivedanta Book Trust (BBT), which manages the international publishing and distribution of his writings.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Apart from his major works, the BBT publishes various paperbacks derived from his lectures.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The BBT also publishes *Back to Godhead*, the magazine Prabhupada founded, in multiple languages.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Between 1973 and 1977, Prabhupada's followers distributed several million books and other pieces of Krishna conscious literature every year in shopping malls, airports, and other public locations in the United States and worldwide.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As of 2023, his books had been translated into eighty-seven languages.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2022, the BBT printed more than two million pieces of literature.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Shrivatsa Goswami has said, "Making these Vaiṣṇava texts available is one of Śrīla Prabhupāda's greatest contributions.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Apart from the masses, his books have also reached well into academic circles and have spurred academic interest in the Caitanya tradition".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Further, he says, "The significance of making these texts available is not merely academic or cultural; it is spiritual.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] *Jñāna*, knowledge, is spread, proper doctrines are made known, people come closer to reality".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Other academics, too, have applauded Prabhupada's publications as his most significant legacy.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] But his edition of *Bhagavad-gita*, in particular, has come in for criticism as well.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Eric Sharpe, scholar of religion, considers Prabhupada's reading of *Bhagavad-gita* single-minded and fundamentalist.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Sinha, takes exception to Prabhupada's "misinterpretations and unkind remarks" directed toward Advaita Vedanta, the philosophy of absolute monism.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The most detailed critical analysis by a Western, non-Hindu scholar comes from historian of religion Robert D.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Baird takes upon himself the task of not merely seeing Prabhupada as "an authentic proponent of Vaishnavism" but of examining as an academic scholar the way Prabhupada reads the *Bhagavad-gita*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Whereas many scholars, Baird writes, see "some degree of progression" in the *Gita*, with different themes emphasized in different parts of the book, Prabhupada "reads the complete teaching of the book, indeed of Vedic literature generally, into any passage".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] It appears "that he considers it legitimate to interpret any verse in the light of the whole system found in the *Gītā* whether it is explicitly mentioned in that verse of the Gītā or not".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In this way, he reads "Krishna consciousness" even into portions of the text where Krishna is not explicitly mentioned.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada cites later passages in the *Gita* to explain earlier passages.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Indeed, he even quotes from other texts in the canon (whether written before the *Gita* or after) to indicate the intention of the *Gita*, "as though they have the same authority as the *Gita* itself".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And so: "In all, a wide range of texts are used to serve as authorities for understanding the *Gītā*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Swami Bhaktivedanta not only treats specific texts in a way that would be unusual among Western scholars, but he sees specific texts in the light of the Vedas in general".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada uses the text of the *Gita* to present various aspects of Krishna theology.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And "he also goes beyond specific texts and the *Gītā* itself when he makes it the occasion for the inculcation of a Vaishnava lifestyle," typified by chanting the *maha-mantra*, regulating one's sexual activity, offering food to Krishna, and following a vegetarian diet.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And so: "Swami Bhaktivedanta is more interested in expounding the principles of Krishna consciousness than in merely explicating the text at hand".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In one instance cited, "the text recommends one thing [*astanga-yoga*] and Bhaktivedanta Swami cancels that and offers the *mahāmantra*".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As for competing interpretations: "Bhaktivedanta often seeks to show the superiority of the Vaishnava position and the error of other positions".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] "The position that is attacked with the most regularity and vigor is that of Advaita Vedanta," "the system of thought that is commonly used to provide the structure for Western understandings of 'Hinduism'", whose advocates Prabhupada calls Mayavadins, impersonalists, or monists.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] For Advaita Vedanta he reserves his strongest condemnations.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Nor does Prabhupada only criticize "impersonalists".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Rather, "Scholars in particular come under Swami Bhaktivedanta's condemnation because they are merely 'mental speculators'".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In Prabhupada's view, Baird says, "Since these scholars are not surrendered to Krishna, they are not Krishna conscious; they are merely offering their own ideas rather than the truth within the *paramparā* system [the lineage of masters and disciples]".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada "seldom engages in the kind of argumentation that scholars are accustomed to when deciding between alternative positions".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Instead he takes a position as a spiritual master within the disciplic succession and "merely declares" what is true.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And so, Baird says, "The gulf between Swami Bhaktivedanta's presentation and that of the scholarly exegete is simply unbridgeable, for their purposes operate on different levels".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] But what some scholars might see as faults, others see as virtues.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Thomas Hopkins sees Prabhupada's translations and purports as successfully conveying the meaning of the text precisely because Prabhupada draws upon the commentaries of his predecessors and brings to his work the understandings of his entire tradition.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Moreover, Hopkins says, Prabhupada does this in such a way that the entire text becomes comprehensible to a modern reader, not only theoretically but practically.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Translations of such texts as the *Gita*, Hopkins says, cannot be done mechanically.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The translator has to understand the spirit and the experience that lie behind the text.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Where Prabhupada's translations expand the text, they do so "for the sake of making the meaning more clear, rather than obscuring it".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Hopkins says, "Writing a commentary is not a merely intellectual or academic exercise—it has a practical goal: to engage people with a living spiritual tradition".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada, he says, brings the meaning of the text out of the past and into the present, giving it meaning in terms of people's lives.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada's efforts to establish and expand Krishna consciousness included some difficulties internal to his new and growing movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He had to train disciples unaccustomed to Vaishnava culture and philosophy and engage them in furthering his Hare Krishna movement; he had to set up and then guide his Governing Body Commission to see to ISKCON's global management.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He often had to intervene when clashes and controversies within ISKCON grew out of hand.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He had to sort out difficulties faced by individual disciples, ensure a proper understanding of his teachings, and, more broadly, transplant an entire cultural movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He also faced challenges from the outside world.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Until the mid-1970s, the attitude of the Western public towards Prabhupada and his movement was cordial.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] News reports described Hare Krishna devotees, their beliefs, and their religious practices in a spirit of curiosity.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The rapidly expanding Hare Krishna movement — distinctive, foreign, highly visible, and vigorous (often over-vigorous) in spreading its message — became an early target for a nascent anti-cult movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The Hare Krishna movement no longer represented an authentic spiritual tradition.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Instead, it was now one of a myriad of "destructive cults" that won converts and took over their lives by "mind control" and "brainwashing".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] When young adults, supposedly robbed of free will and "programmed" by mind control, became Hare Krishna devotees, some parents hired "deprogrammers" to kidnap them and "free them from the cult".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] "Deprogrammings" typically involved days or weeks of isolation, browbeating, and intense verbal haranguing and harassment.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After one such deprogramming failed, the New York City District Attorney's Office charged two local Hare Krishna leaders with illegally imprisoning two Hare Krishna followers by brainwashing them.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada instructed his disciples to fight these charges, among other ways, by entering his books into evidence.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Meanwhile, two hundred scholars signed a document defending ISKCON as an authentic Indian missionary movement.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In March 1977, a New York State Supreme Court justice threw out the charges and recognized ISKCON as a bona fide religious tradition.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Nonetheless, in America and Europe the "cult" label and image persisted for the rest of Prabhupada's lifetime and beyond.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As scholar James Beckford notes, in the 1970s, Hare Krishna devotees became increasingly active in selling their literature and collecting donations from the public, so they were sharply criticized for what was seen as harassing people for money at airports and other public places.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As Bryant and Ekstrand comment, "Questionable fund-raising tactics, confrontational attitudes to mainstream authorities, and an isolationist mentality, coupled with the excesses of neophyte proselytizing zeal, brought public disapproval" — something that Prabhupada had to deal with too.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As ISKCON evolved towards being a worldwide organization, it suffered from the inevitable travails of institutionalization.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Young disciples, mostly from an anti-establishment, anti-authoritarian background, became members of the GBC and found themselves running a worldwide institution.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Preaching sometimes started giving way to revenue production; gender issues arose; leaders sometimes fell, and scandals broke out.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Bureaucracy intruded on spontaneity, and many members left.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] As much as Prabhupada tried to leave management to the GBC, much of this he too had to deal with personally.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada directed his disciples to train children in boarding schools called *gurukulas*, where they would receive education from spiritual teachers.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] However, as reported by sociologist of religion E.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Burke Rochford, through mismanagement, these schools became like orphanages.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After Prabhupada's departure, it came to light that physical and sexual abuse occurred within these schools due to lack of oversight.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In India, Prabhupada faced a special set of challenges.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He had much to accomplish there, but his American and European disciples were inexperienced in how to get things done in India and even how to live there.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] When Prabhupada's young American followers came to India in the early 1970s and began holding festivals, including public *sankirtana*, many Indians were surprised to see Westerners adopting Indian modes of worship and devotion.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Some local people, including even some Indian officials, suspected that the American devotees must be undercover operatives of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Outspoken and uncompromising as he was in the way he presented Krishna's teachings in India, as elsewhere, Prabhupada found himself battling with opposing views of all sorts.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Therefore, another challenge came from Prabhupada's consistent rejection of the common Hindu notion of caste by birth.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Since Prabhupada, like his predecessors, insisted that anyone, from any race or nation, could become spiritually purified and fit to perform the duties of priests, he faced opposition from Hindu brahmins who held that performing such duties was an exclusive birthright of their caste.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] When Prabhupada resolved to build a temple on land in Juhu, Bombay (now Mumbai), the man who had sold ISKCON the land tried to swindle the devotees and take it back.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The man had deep political connections in the Bombay municipality and employed lawyers and even thugs to drive the devotees off, but Prabhupada persisted and eventually won.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] While working to establish his movement, Prabhupada had to deal with problems caused even by leading disciples, who, monks or not, could still hold on to intellectual baggage, disdain for authority, and ambitions for power.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1968 Prabhupada's first *sannyasi* disciple openly disregarded Prabhupada's instructions to him and twisted core tenets of Prabhupada's teachings.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] This foreshadowed succession problems and issues of authority that Prabhupada's movement would face both during Prabhupada's presence and after.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Unlike Indian gurus who declared themselves *avatars*, divine appearances of God, Prabhupada, from the very beginning of his preaching, called himself only a servant or representative of God.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] But in 1970 four of Prabhupada's early *sannyasis* announced at a large ISKCON gathering that Prabhupada's followers had failed to recognize that Prabhupada was Krishna: God Himself.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada expelled those *sannyasis* from his Society (he eventually readmitted them after they recanted their claim).
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1972, without consulting Prabhupada, eight of the twelve members of the GBC held a meeting in New York aimed at centralizing control of ISKCON's activities and finances.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Their plans would have lessened Prabhupada's own oversight and set aside his emphasis on the autonomy of each ISKCON center.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] This prompted Prabhupada to suspend the entire GBC "until further notice", establish direct lines of communication with each temple's leaders, and re-emphasize spiritual purity, the selfless and voluntary nature of devotional life, and the exemplary conduct befitting ISKCON leaders.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He said he wanted this, not corporate bureaucracy and excessive centralization.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1975, a clash broke out when a team of ten parties of itinerant *sannyasis*, assisted by two hundred *brahmacharis*, crisscrossed America, visiting ISKCON temples to extoll renunciation and a missionary spirit — and urge *brahmacharis* to abandon the temples and join the *sannyasi* parties.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The temples, the team argued, were led by presidents who were *grihasthas* (married men), and grihasthas had a propensity for enjoyment that undermined what should be an austere temple atmosphere.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The conflict reached its peak in 1976 in Mayapur at ISKCON's annual global gathering when a *sannyasi*-dominated GBC passed resolutions severely restricting the role of women and families in ISKCON.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After hearing from both sides, Prabhupada came down against this type of discrimination, calling it "fanaticism", and had the GBC undo the resolutions.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada said, "I cannot discriminate — man, woman, child, rich, poor, educated, or foolish.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Let them all come, and let them take Krishna consciousness".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In the course of his preaching work in the West, Prabhupada made controversial statements that criticized various ideals of modern society or spoke offensively of certain groups.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] "In a traditional Hindu vein", Prabhupada spoke favorably of the myth of Aryan bloodlines and compared darker races to *shudras* [people of low caste], thus implying them being inferior to the lighter-complexioned humans.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In a recorded room conversation with disciples in 1977, he calls African Americans "uncultured and drunkards", further stating that after being given freedom and equal rights, they caused a disturbance in the society.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada called democracy "the government of the asses", "nonsense", and "farce", at the same time praising the monarchial form of government and speaking favorably of dictatorship.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] While comparing Napoleon and Hitler to great demons of Hindu mythology Hiranyakashipu and Kamsa, he called their activities "very great".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] On other occasions, he made "generally approving remarks about Hitler" and said that Hitler and his regime carried out the Holocaust because Jews "were financing against Germany".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He also expressed some misogynistic views, asserting that "women cannot properly utilize freedom and it is better for them to be dependent", stating that they are "generally not very intelligent", and "in general should not be trusted".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Scholars have commented, however, on the contrast between such controversial pronouncements and the full picture of what Prabhupada actually taught and did.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Kim Knott, a religious studies scholar, extensively discusses Prabhupada's statements about women.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Describing her perspective about ISKCON as that of an "outsider" and a "western feminist", she highlights Prabhupada's firm belief that "bhakti-yoga", the path of Krishna Consciousness, allows transcendence beyond gender distinctions.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Knott emphasizes that, according to Prabhupada, women devotees, regardless of their gender, possess equal potential for spiritual advancement and service to Krishna.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] She further commends Prabhupada for opening up the Hare Krishna movement to women despite cultural norms and traditional prescriptions.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In this way, she writes, Prabhupada took time, place, and circumstance into account and acted in the spirit of Krishna consciousness, "in the manner of Chaitanya".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Commenting on the role and degree of responsibility that Prabhupada's statements about women played in their abuse in ISKCON, E.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Burke Rochford notes that Prabhupada's personal example in dealings with his earliest women disciples was "far more important".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Their collective personal experiences, Rochford observes, portray Prabhupada's "respectful attitude and behavior toward his women disciples" and his empowerment for the same rights and duties as his male disciples.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada encouraged and engaged women in conducting public scriptural discourses, *kirtans* and temple worship, writing for ISKCON magazines and publications, personally accompanying and assisting him, and assuming "significant institutional positions in ISKCON".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Similarly, scholar of religion Akshay Gupta observes that Prabhupada did not regard his black disciples as lower or "untouchables", displaying to some of them the same or even greater degree of affection than to his followers of other ethnicities.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Another scholar of religion Mans Broo adds that when Prabhupada speaks about castes, he referred to an envisioned "ideal society" in which people would be divided into different occupational groups "based not on hereditary but on individual qualifications".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] However, Broo concludes that this behavior does not clear Prabhupada from responsibility for his more radical, politically incorrect statements.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Still, others are willing to differentiate between his statements they deem "absolute" and those they consider "relative", acknowledging that some teachings may be contingent on the circumstances of Prabhupada's life before coming to the US.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] However, some followers view this approach as "exceedingly risky", questioning who has the authority to determine which teachings are relative and which are not.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Therefore, Broo concludes, this issue is "not likely to be resolved soon".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] By explaining the teachings of bhakti yoga and Gaudiya Vaishnavism and arousing interest in them worldwide, Prabhupada made a lasting contribution.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Through his writings and his movement, many Westerners have become aware of *bhakti* for the first time.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] He translated and commented on important spiritual texts, particularly the *Bhagavad-gita*, the *Srimad-Bhagavatam*, and the *Caitanya-caritamrta*, making these texts accessible to a global audience.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] His commentaries brought the traditional wisdom of these writings into a contemporary context, making possible a deeper comprehension of their spiritual meaning and its practical application in one's life.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Within Gaudiya Vaishnavism, Prabhupada's preaching achievements are viewed as the fulfillment of a mission to introduce Caitanya Mahaprabhu's teachings to the world.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada also spread the chanting of the *Hare Krishna mantra* worldwide.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2013, Rochford wrote, "[T]he fact that ISKCON has survived for nearly 50 years, despite significant change, is a testament to the devotees' resilience and to the power of Prabhupada's teachings and vision for ISKCON".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In India, Prabhupada's movement has become a well-respected institution, with recognition at all levels of Hindu society.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] ISKCON has large temple complexes active in cities like Mumbai, New Delhi, Bengaluru, Chennai, and Kolkata.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] ISKCON's center in Mayapur has become an Eastern Indian place of pilgrimage for millions every year.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Thousands of middle-class Hindus, both in India and elsewhere, have joined ISKCON.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And Hindus both in India and in the Hindu diaspora have provided ISKCON vast support.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] But Prabhupada's legacy also faces scrutiny on various fronts.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Criticisms have emerged regarding the movement's organizational structure, controversies have arisen surrounding continuity of leadership after his death, and misdeeds and even criminal acts have been committed by some ISKCON members, including once-respected former leaders.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Concerns have been expressed about the movement's adaptability to modern values, especially concerning gender roles and societal norms.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] And although ISKCON has benefited from the support and participation of a large and growing number of Indian families in its congregations outside India, the "Hinduization" of ISKCON has in many places tended to diminish the involvement of other audiences.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Nonetheless, Prabhupada's influence endures through his writings and ISKCON's ongoing activities.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Despite significant setbacks, the movement he started continues to grow.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Kim Knott writes that scholars describe Prabhupada as a charismatic spiritual leader and emphasize his "humanity" and "uniqueness".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada's missionary successes in such a short period, and at such an advanced age, she writes, are extolled by scholars using terms such as "stunning", "remarkable", and "extraordinary".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In the same vein, Klaus Klostermaier, scholar of Hinduism and Indian history, refers to Prabhupada as "probably, the most successful propagator of Hinduism abroad".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada's success in spreading Indian spirituality among non-Indians across the world brought him acclaim from Indian political leaders.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Indian Prime Ministers Atal Bihari Vajpayee, Deve Gowda, Narendra Modi, and Indian Presidents Shankar Dayal Sharma, Pranab Mukherjee, and Pratibha Patil have praised Prabhupada, his work and mission.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] On the fiftieth anniversary of Prabhupada's voyage to the West, US Congresswoman Tulsi Gabbard praised the "compassion that drove Srila Prabhupada to attempt something so brave and so daring to deliver the message of Lord Chaitanya and the Holy Name to all of mankind".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] On 4 December 2025, Prime Minister of India Narendra Modi presented a Russian copy of Prabhupada's *Bhagavad-Gita As It Is* to the President of Russia Vladimir Putin during Putin's state visit to India, writing in his official X account: "Presented a copy of the Gita in Russian to President Putin.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The teachings of the Gita give inspiration to millions across the world." The note added to the gift explained: "Its timeless wisdom inspires ethical living, mind control, and inner peace, with translations making it accessible to modern readers worldwide".
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In keeping with *Gaudiya-Vaisnava* rites, after Prabhupada's death at the Krishna-Balarama temple in Vrindavan (Uttar Pradesh, India), his disciples interred his body on the temple premises and erected a marble *samadhi*, or shrine, over his burial site.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In Mayapur (West Bengal), they built a much larger *pushpa-samadhi* — a shrine sanctified with flowers from Prabhupada's burial ceremony.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Daily *puja* (traditional worship) is offered to larger-than-life statues of Prabhupada at both sites.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Another shrine is dedicated to Prabhupada in New Vrindaban (West Virginia, USA), where a residence built to host Prabhupada during his occasional visits evolved into the elaborate Prabhupada's Palace of Gold.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After opening to the public in 1979, two years after Prabhupada's death, the memorial site is now a place of worship and an attraction for pilgrims and tourists, listed in America's National Register of Historic Places.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Other rooms ‌in which Prabhupada stayed while in Vrindavan, Mumbai, Los Angeles, London, Melbourne and several other places around the world have been preserved as museums.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Prabhupada's birthplace, in the Tollygunge neighborhood of Kolkata, was inaugurated as a memorial site in 2021, on the 125th anniversary of Prabhupada's birth, by West Bengal Chief Minister Mamata Banerjee.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In the Ultadanga neighborhood of Kolkata, the building, known as Bhaktivinode Asan where Prabhupada first met his guru, Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati, has also been restored as a heritage site.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The monument was created in two parts — one depicting Prabhupada's departure for America, the other his arrival.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] After the monument was unveiled, the "departure" part was installed at the ISKCON temple in Kolkata, the "arrival" part in front of the ISKCON temple in Boston.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In November 2024, Scottish Church College inaugurated the "Abhay Charan Seminar Hall", honoring A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The hall was constructed with support from the Bhaktivedanta Research Center.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2008, Ketola wrote that there were more than thirty historical, biographical, and autobiographical works centering on Prabhupada.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Satsvarupa Dasa Goswami's official six-volume biography *Srila Prabhupada-lilamrta* ("carefully researched", Ketola reports) has more recently been joined by a shorter biography, *Swami in a Strange Land*, by Joshua Greene.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Both authors are Prabhupada's disciples.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Ketola also notes two published diaries kept by direct assistants of Prabhupada: Tamal Krishna Goswami's *TKG's Diary* and Hari Sauri Dasa's multi-volume *Transcendental Diary*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] List of biographical publications about A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1996 Gaurav Seth produced the fifty-five-minute biographical film *Prabhupada: A Lifetime in Preparation*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2017 John Griesser, a Prabhupada disciple, produced an uncritical 91-minute film: *Hare Krishna!
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The Mantra, the Movement, and the Swami who started it All*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Disciples have also undertaken two video projects collecting memories of Srila Prabhupada, one entitled *Remembering Srila Prabhupada*, the other *Following Srila Prabhupada*.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] The Bhaktivedanta Archives, in North Carolina, serves as a repository for Srila Prabhupada's manuscripts and letters, for photographs of Srila Prabhupada, and for audio recordings.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] on Prabhupada's 125th birth anniversary.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1996, the Government of India issued a commemorative stamp in Prabhupada's honor and in 2021 a 125-rupee commemorative coin.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2001, the City of New York installed a plaque in Tompkins Square Park to mark the "Hare Krishna tree", the elm under which Prabhupada and his early followers first began chanting the *Hare Krishna mantra* in 1966.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Various ISKCON-related schools and other institutions have been named after Srila Prabhupada, including the Bhaktivedanta Research Center in Kolkata, which holds a full collection of the works of Bhaktisiddhanta Sarasvati as well as publications from the first twenty years of the Gaudiya Math.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 2023, Scottish Church College and the Bhaktivedanta Research Center jointly established the "A.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada Memorial Award" to commemorate Prabhupada's student years at the college, meant to recognize both the most meritorious student for outstanding academic achievements and a faculty member for exceptional community service.
[src:ahimsa/a-c-bhaktivedanta-swami-prabhupada-p02] In 1978, a prominent entrance road into Vrindavan was named Bhaktivedanta Swami Marg after Prabhupada.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:ahimsa/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:ahimsa/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The word *Ahimsa*—sometimes spelled *Ahinsa*—derives from the Sanskrit root *hiṃs*, meaning to strike; *hiṃsā* is injury or harm, while *a-hiṃsā* (prefixed with the alpha privative), its opposite, is *non-harming* or *nonviolence*.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Reverence for *ahimsa* can be found in Jain, Hindu, and Buddhist canonical texts.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Lord Parshvanatha (the 23rd of Jainism's 24 Tirthankaras) is said to have preached *ahimsa* as one of the four vows.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Scholars describe nonviolence as a central doctrinal and practical principle of Jainism, developed to an extent that distinguishes it from most other religious traditions of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] 1500 BCE) is the oldest surviving text in India, but many scholars believe the specific ethical practice of *ahimsa* originated in the non-Vedic *Sramana* traditions (which include Jainism and Buddhism) before being absorbed into Brahmanism.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Deshmukh, suggest that the roots of *ahimsa* and asceticism may date to the Indus Valley Civilisation (c.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] 3300–1300 BCE), citing the discovery of seals depicting figures in the *kayotsarga* (standing meditation) posture common to Jain iconography.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Indologist Johannes Bronkhorst has proposed the "Greater Magadha" theory, arguing that the eastern Gangetic plain (modern Bihar/Bengal) developed a distinct non-Vedic culture where concepts like *Karma*, rebirth, and *ahimsa* originated.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] According to this view, the Vedic priesthood later adopted these concepts as they expanded eastward.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Similarly, the German Indologist Ludwig Alsdorf argued that *ahimsa* likely began not as a moral rule but as a "magico-ritualistic" taboo against killing or harming living beings, which was part of a pan-Indian or pre-Aryan heritage later refined into an ethical system by the Jains.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The concept of *ahimsa* evolved gradually within the Vedic tradition.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] 1500–1000 BCE), animal sacrifice was a central component of ritual life.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Then the concept transitioned from a ritualistic concern-avoiding injury to the sacrificer or the minute details of the ritual—to an internalized ethical virtue.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] By the late Vedic era, texts like the *Chandogya Upanishad* (c.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] 8th century BCE) explicitly listed *ahimsa* as one of five essential virtues (along with truthfulness and charity).
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The *Yajurveda* reflects this shifting ethos with prayers for universal peace, such as: "May all beings look at me with a friendly eye, may I do likewise, and may we look at each other with the eyes of a friend".
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The principle of *ahimsa* moved from personal asceticism to state policy under the Mauryan Emperor Ashoka (c.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Following the Kalinga War, Ashoka renounced military conquest in favor of "conquest by Dharma".
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] His Rock Edicts restricted animal slaughter, established medical care for animals, and promoted nonviolence as a civic duty, embedding the Shramanic value of *ahimsa* into India's political fabric.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] In Jainism, the understanding and implementation of *ahimsa* is more radical, scrupulous, and comprehensive than in any other religion.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Killing any living being out of passions like attachment is considered *hiṃsā* (to injure) and abstaining from such an act is *ahimsā* (noninjury).
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The vow of *ahimsā* is considered the foremost among the "five vows of Jainism".
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Other vows like truth (*satya*) are meant for safeguarding the vow of *ahimsā*.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The statement *ahimsā paramo dharmaḥ* (or, "Non-injury/nonviolence/harmlessness is the supreme/ultimate/paramount/highest/absolute duty/virtue/attribute/religion") is often found inscribed on the walls of the Jain temples.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] As in Hinduism, the aim is to prevent the accumulation of harmful karma.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The Jain concept of *ahimsa* is characterised by detailed classifications of life.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Jains categorize living beings (*jiva*) based on their sensory faculties (*indriyas*), ranging from one-sensed beings (plants, water, earth) to five-sensed beings (humans, animals).
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Killing of animals for food is absolutely ruled out.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Jains also make considerable efforts not to injure plants in everyday life as far as possible.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Though they admit that plants must be destroyed for the sake of food, they accept such violence only inasmuch as it is indispensable for human survival, and there are special instructions for preventing unnecessary violence against plants.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Jain monks and nuns go out of their way so as not to hurt even small insects and other minuscule animals.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Both the renouncers and the laypeople of Jain faith reject meat, fish, alcohol, and honey as these are believed to harm large or minuscule life forms.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] In the practice of *ahimsa*, the requirements are less strict for the lay persons (*sravakas*) who have undertaken *anuvrata* (Smaller Vows) than for the Jain monastics who are bound by the Mahavrata "Great Vows".
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Jain scholars have debated the potential injury to other life forms during one's occupation.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Certain Jain texts (according to Padmanabh Jaini, a Jainism scholar) forbid people of its faith from husbandry, agriculture, and trade in animal-derived products.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Some Jains abstain from farming because it inevitably entails unintentional killing or injuring of many small animals, such as worms and insects.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] These teachings, in part, have led the Jain community to focus on trade, merchant, clerical, and administrative occupations to minimize *arambhaja-himsa* (occupational violence against all life forms).
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] For the layperson, the teaching has been of *ahimsa* with *pramada* – that is, reducing violence through proper intention and being careful in every action on a daily basis to minimize violence to all life forms.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] When Mahavira revived and reorganised the Jain faith in the 6th or 5th century BCE, *ahimsa* was already an established, strictly observed rule.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Rishabhanatha (Ādinātha), the first Jain Tirthankara, whom modern Western historians consider to be a historical figure, followed by Parshvanatha (Pārśvanātha) the twenty-third Tirthankara lived in about the 9th century BCE.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] He founded the community to which Mahavira's parents belonged.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Ahimsa was already part of the "Fourfold Restraint" (*Caujjama*), the vows taken by Parshva's followers.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] In the times of Mahavira and in the following centuries, Jains were at odds with both Buddhists and followers of the Vedic religion or Hindus, whom they accused of negligence and inconsistency in the implementation of *ahimsa*.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] According to the Jain tradition either lacto vegetarianism or veganism is prescribed.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] The Jain texts, unlike most Hindu and Buddhist texts on just war, have been inconsistent.
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] For its monastic community – *sadhu* and *sadhvi* – the historically accepted practice has been to "willingly sacrifice one's own life" to the attacker, to not retaliate, so that the mendicant may keep the First Great Vow of "total nonviolence".
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] Jain literature of the 10th century CE, for example, describes a king ready for war and being given lessons about non-violence by the Jain acharya (spiritual teacher).
[src:ahimsa/ahimsa] In the 12th century CE and thereafter, in an era of violent raids, destruction of temples, the slaughter of agrarian communities and ascetics by Islamic armies, Jain scholars reconsidered the First Great Vow of mendicants and its parallel for the laypeople.
